00:33.072 --> 00:34.355
Glad you could make it,
Dan.

00:34.357 --> 00:35.990
Well, I'm sorry
I'm late to the party.

00:36.025 --> 00:37.358
Was shoring up
the southern wall

00:37.360 --> 00:40.861
in case the damn skitters
attacked again.

00:40.913 --> 00:43.581
We gonna use that thing to bomb
the bastards, like last time?

00:43.616 --> 00:44.915
Not like last time.

00:44.951 --> 00:46.750
A toy plane
carries a toy bomb.

00:46.786 --> 00:49.703
Wouldn't even make a dent
in that mess.

00:49.705 --> 00:51.005
Unbelievable.

00:51.040 --> 00:53.707
There's twice as many
as before.

00:53.709 --> 00:55.593
Dingaan:
Ah, not to worry.

00:55.628 --> 00:57.711
This should take them all out
in one fell swoop.

00:57.763 --> 00:59.213
I cooked down
the leftover fertilizer,

00:59.215 --> 01:00.714
made white phosphorus.

01:00.766 --> 01:02.266
W.P.?

01:02.301 --> 01:05.269
I've seen that used
in some wars. It's nasty stuff.

01:05.304 --> 01:07.354
We added an aerosol sprayer
onto the bottom of this drone.

01:07.390 --> 01:09.890
So we're gonna crop-dust
the whole valley with it.

01:09.942 --> 01:12.109
That's the plan.
Genius.

01:12.144 --> 01:14.061
Anne:
They're feeding on croomia.

01:14.063 --> 01:15.863
We studied it
in med school.

01:15.898 --> 01:18.148
It's rare, but it has great
medicinal and nutritional value.

01:18.200 --> 01:20.784
Everything a growing skitter
needs in order to attack us.

01:20.820 --> 01:22.202
Once that stuff
is gone...

01:22.238 --> 01:23.704
We'll be
back on the menu.

01:23.739 --> 01:24.822
So let's do this.

01:24.874 --> 01:26.874
[ Whirring ]

01:47.763 --> 01:49.396
Good job.

01:49.432 --> 01:51.765
[ Skitters chittering ]

01:54.737 --> 01:55.936
Wait for it.

01:55.988 --> 01:58.939
Wait for it.

01:59.909 --> 02:01.025
Now.

02:01.077 --> 02:02.159
[ Click ]

02:11.370 --> 02:13.704
[ All cheering ]

02:17.793 --> 02:19.960
[ Skitters groaning ]

02:23.067 --> 02:27.067
<font color=#00FF00>♪ Falling Skies 5x03 ♪</font>
<font color=#00FFFF>Hatchlings</font>
Original Air Date on July 12, 2015

02:27.068 --> 02:33.068
== sync, corrected by <font color=#00FF00>elderman</font> ==
<font color=#00FFFF>@elder_man</font>

02:33.225 --> 02:34.975
<i>So far, our primary focus</i>

02:35.027 --> 02:37.695
<i>has been on dismantling</i>
<i>dormant Espheni technology,</i>

02:37.730 --> 02:39.897
<i>preventing the enemy</i>
<i>from becoming a threat</i>

02:39.949 --> 02:42.199
<i>should they get</i>
<i>their power core back online.</i>

02:42.234 --> 02:43.984
<i>And from there, it's simple.</i>

02:44.036 --> 02:46.370
<i>Kill as many of their</i>
<i>bio-creations as possible</i>

02:46.405 --> 02:48.155
<i>and advance.</i>

02:48.157 --> 02:50.324
<i>If all the militias</i>
<i>around the globe do this,</i>

02:50.326 --> 02:52.159
<i>we can gut</i>
<i>the Espheni war machine</i>

02:52.161 --> 02:53.961
<i>and take back our home.</i>

02:53.996 --> 02:56.130
Okay, okay. I don't think
we need to watch that again.

02:56.165 --> 02:58.799
I had no idea
you were such a natural.

02:58.834 --> 03:00.801
It's time
for a personal stylist.

03:00.836 --> 03:03.053
Apparently, even the Volm
cameras add 10 pounds.

03:03.089 --> 03:04.304
Under my father's orders,

03:04.340 --> 03:06.140
the Volm
distributed this message

03:06.175 --> 03:08.175
to every rebel group
we could locate worldwide.

03:08.227 --> 03:09.893
The good news is

03:09.929 --> 03:12.146
that these Mason militias
have been quite successful.

03:12.181 --> 03:13.480
Wait --
"Mason militias"?

03:13.516 --> 03:17.234
No, they --
they can't call them that.

03:17.269 --> 03:19.853
So far,
your global coalition

03:19.855 --> 03:23.991
has destroyed an estimated 52%
of all Espheni technology.

03:24.026 --> 03:25.826
Good. Good.
You said "good news."

03:25.861 --> 03:27.277
What's the bad news?

03:27.329 --> 03:30.030
This gray area,
less than a square mile,

03:30.032 --> 03:33.167
is inaccessible
to our reconnaissance efforts.

03:33.202 --> 03:34.202
That's Fayetteville.

03:34.253 --> 03:35.753
They're jamming you,
aren't they?

03:35.788 --> 03:38.172
To hide what?
Why?

03:38.207 --> 03:41.041
It could be an early effort
to launch a new power core.

03:41.043 --> 03:42.509
But if they don't have
power,

03:42.545 --> 03:44.378
how can they power
a jamming device?

03:44.380 --> 03:47.431
The power core was supporting
their greater war machine --

03:47.466 --> 03:48.932
Beamers, mechs.

03:48.968 --> 03:50.884
Which we're
systematically disabling.

03:50.886 --> 03:51.969
Yes.

03:52.021 --> 03:53.554
However,
the Espheni also have

03:53.556 --> 03:56.356
self-contained energy mechanisms
for smaller applications,

03:56.392 --> 03:58.025
such as
communication transmitters.

03:58.060 --> 03:59.560
Jamming devices.

03:59.562 --> 04:02.312
Bottom line -- we underestimate
this enemy at our peril.

04:02.364 --> 04:05.899
Apparently, they're up to
<i>something</i> in Fayetteville.

04:05.951 --> 04:08.118
We take the 2nd Mass there,
and we stop them.

04:08.154 --> 04:12.122
What's this other static here,
up in the northeast?

04:12.158 --> 04:15.042
Jesus Christ.
That's Washington, D.C.

04:15.077 --> 04:16.160
Uh-huh.

04:17.463 --> 04:19.296
What the hell's going on
in D.C.?

04:19.331 --> 04:22.382
We do not know,
Tom Mason.

04:22.418 --> 04:23.834
Not yet.

04:35.598 --> 04:37.014
Hey.

04:38.400 --> 04:40.100
You should eat.

04:43.322 --> 04:47.024
[ Growling ]

04:50.246 --> 04:51.945
[ Screeches ]

04:53.616 --> 04:56.500
[ Whimpers ]

04:56.535 --> 04:58.418
Is there anything else
I can --

04:58.454 --> 05:00.087
Yeah --
keep your promise.

05:00.122 --> 05:02.289
You said you could
make my brother better.

05:02.291 --> 05:05.592
[ Snarling, roaring ]

05:05.628 --> 05:07.427
I'm so sorry.

05:07.463 --> 05:10.464
You knew
it couldn't be done.

05:10.516 --> 05:12.850
You just wanted
to steal our food.

05:12.885 --> 05:14.384
[ Munching ]

05:16.272 --> 05:17.437
Is that him?

05:17.473 --> 05:20.307
Is that Brian?

05:20.359 --> 05:21.525
Yep.

05:21.560 --> 05:25.979
Only picture
I could recover.

05:25.981 --> 05:29.283
He's 8 here. I'm 11.

05:30.653 --> 05:33.487
For what it's worth,
I think you're safer with us.

05:33.489 --> 05:35.239
But is <i> he?</i>

05:35.291 --> 05:36.990
[ Growls ]

05:37.042 --> 05:38.375
[ Gasps ]

05:38.410 --> 05:40.410
[ Roars ]

05:40.462 --> 05:42.496
[ Groans ]

05:42.498 --> 05:44.548
[ Deep voice ] C-Catie?

05:47.503 --> 05:48.886
What just happened?

05:48.921 --> 05:50.220
[ Normal voice ]
Noth-- I-I have to go.

05:50.256 --> 05:52.389
That was him.
That was Brian.

05:52.424 --> 05:55.142
He was the only one
that ever called me Catie.

05:56.512 --> 05:58.562
I think
'cause we both have Espheni DNA,

05:58.597 --> 06:00.180
I can connect
to his mind.

06:00.182 --> 06:02.266
Can you let me
talk to him?

06:02.318 --> 06:04.902
No, I-I-I don't think
this is a good idea.

06:04.937 --> 06:05.986
Then you <i> can.</i>

06:06.021 --> 06:07.187
[ Grunts ]

06:07.239 --> 06:09.489
Will you?

06:09.525 --> 06:11.074
Please. Please.

06:11.110 --> 06:13.160
[ Voice breaking ]
I've spent months praying

06:13.195 --> 06:14.912
that my brother
was still in there.

06:14.947 --> 06:18.198
He's the only family
I have left.

06:18.200 --> 06:19.950
[ Roars ]

06:25.958 --> 06:27.207
[ Deep voice ] Love...

06:29.712 --> 06:31.345
...you.

06:31.380 --> 06:32.429
Brian?

06:34.266 --> 06:35.599
Pain.
What can I do?

06:35.634 --> 06:37.384
Can I take away the pain
somehow?

06:37.386 --> 06:38.969
Hurt!
[ Roars ]

06:39.021 --> 06:41.605
You!
[ Grunting ]

06:44.226 --> 06:47.311
No, no, no, no!
Don't stop -- please! Please!

06:47.363 --> 06:50.564
[ Normal voice ] I-I didn't break the
connection. <i>He</i> broke the connection.

06:56.071 --> 06:58.288
What did he mean
about hurting me?

06:58.324 --> 07:02.242
I just --
I think that he...

07:02.244 --> 07:04.711
He wants you to know
that he -- he loves you,

07:04.747 --> 07:06.246
and he doesn't want
to hurt you,

07:06.248 --> 07:08.165
but he doesn't know
if he can help himself.

07:18.260 --> 07:21.678
[ Skitters chittering ]

07:21.730 --> 07:23.096
You hear that?

07:23.148 --> 07:25.015
I heard it
when I was on patrol.

07:25.067 --> 07:26.683
Came up here
to check it out.

07:31.690 --> 07:33.357
Tom:
It's a bottomless pit.

07:33.409 --> 07:35.442
Weaver: They're streaming in
through that choke point.

07:35.494 --> 07:38.028
What are they waiting for?

07:38.080 --> 07:40.163
Must have an overlord.

07:40.199 --> 07:42.666
Question is,
where is he?

07:42.701 --> 07:45.118
Where's he getting
all the skitters?

07:48.044 --> 07:50.379
We are wasting
too much time on this.

07:50.431 --> 07:51.880
We can't even get out
of the starting gate.

07:51.932 --> 07:53.849
I gave an order
to the other militias

07:53.884 --> 07:55.217
that I can't
even follow myself.

07:55.219 --> 07:57.019
Maybe that's the point --
the Espheni stall us

07:57.054 --> 07:58.770
with skitters and hornets
till they can get

07:58.806 --> 08:01.023
their remaining tech weapons
back online.

08:01.058 --> 08:03.058
Why don't we just
crop-dust them again?

08:03.060 --> 08:05.143
We could, but I only have enough
fertilizer for one more batch.

08:05.195 --> 08:06.862
Doesn't matter, anyway.

08:06.897 --> 08:08.981
The Espheni are replacing them
as fast as we can kill them.

08:09.033 --> 08:10.816
But how are they
replacing them?

08:10.868 --> 08:13.902
They were pouring into that
valley like starving children.

08:13.904 --> 08:16.822
I'm just wondering if they're
reproducing them somehow.

08:16.874 --> 08:18.790
Reproducing?
They're <i> making</i> them?

08:18.826 --> 08:19.958
Yes -- biologically.

08:19.994 --> 08:21.326
I mean, we know

08:21.378 --> 08:23.128
that their mechanical weapons
are down, right?

08:23.163 --> 08:24.796
They have no Beamers,
no mechs,

08:24.832 --> 08:26.832
so all that's left
are biological weapons.

08:26.884 --> 08:28.467
Hornets and skitters --
they don't need power.

08:28.502 --> 08:29.885
They just need to eat.

08:29.920 --> 08:31.503
So the Espheni
are growing them?

08:31.555 --> 08:33.255
Maybe -- I mean,
we know they're obsessed

08:33.307 --> 08:34.423
with DNA,
genetic mutations.

08:34.475 --> 08:35.841
Like Brian.

08:35.893 --> 08:37.509
Right. And that insect
that we caught.

08:37.561 --> 08:38.561
[ Clank ]

08:38.562 --> 08:40.595
Now what?

08:46.520 --> 08:48.403
Anthony, what happened?!

08:48.439 --> 08:50.405
I heard a noise,
and I came in to check.

08:50.441 --> 08:52.441
Anne!
[ Grunts ]

08:52.443 --> 08:54.359
Weaver:
What happened, Anthony?

08:54.411 --> 08:55.411
[ Groans ]

08:55.412 --> 08:57.112
Soon as I got in here,

08:57.164 --> 08:59.581
that...thing
extended its freakin' arm,

08:59.616 --> 09:02.367
shot his claw out like one of
those telescoping Billy clubs

09:02.419 --> 09:04.453
I used to carry
as a cop.

09:04.505 --> 09:06.338
I was -- I was
all the way over here,

09:06.373 --> 09:09.007
and it just grabbed me and
slammed my head into the wall.

09:09.043 --> 09:11.426
All right, that's it! We hunt
this thing down, and we kill it.

09:11.462 --> 09:13.428
No. We don't have time
to go hunting right now.

09:13.464 --> 09:15.213
You're saying we're not
gonna go looking for this?

09:15.265 --> 09:16.882
Yeah, that's exactly what
I'm saying. We leave it alone.

09:16.934 --> 09:18.300
If it comes back,
you all have my permission

09:18.302 --> 09:19.434
to shoot it on sight.

09:19.470 --> 09:20.552
Weaver:
Wait a minute, Tom.

09:20.604 --> 09:23.472
He ran.
He didn't hurt anybody.

09:23.524 --> 09:25.974
He could have come after
any of us. He didn't.

09:27.911 --> 09:29.311
What about Caitlin?

09:29.363 --> 09:31.113
D-dragged her away.

09:32.116 --> 09:33.982
Maggie.

09:33.984 --> 09:35.534
I put them in this position.
I need to take responsibility.

09:35.569 --> 09:36.535
I need you
with the 2nd Mass.

09:36.570 --> 09:38.070
I'm going.
Damn it! Maggie!

09:41.208 --> 09:43.158
You can't go alone.

09:43.210 --> 09:45.494
Your dad's right --
you guys should all be focused

09:45.546 --> 09:47.462
on finding the source
of those skitters.

09:47.498 --> 09:50.632
Yeah, and you need somebody
to watch your back.

09:50.667 --> 09:53.001
Who knows
what that thing is --

09:53.003 --> 09:54.419
He's a person.

09:54.471 --> 09:56.555
Okay, person --
...is capable of.

09:56.590 --> 09:58.640
I don't want to put you
in that position with your dad.

09:58.675 --> 10:00.509
My dad, my problem.

10:01.929 --> 10:03.228
Then let's gear up.

10:06.600 --> 10:08.567
I thought you weren't
supposed to be on duty.

10:08.602 --> 10:10.318
Couldn't sleep.

10:10.354 --> 10:12.521
Kept wanting to see
that damn mutant for myself,

10:12.523 --> 10:15.607
see how they tried
to make a human more like them.

10:16.944 --> 10:18.944
That mutant has a name,
you know?

10:18.996 --> 10:21.363
Yeah,<i> used</i> to have a name.
Now it's a goddamn Espheni.

10:21.415 --> 10:23.532
All right. Relax.

10:29.123 --> 10:30.372
You finished?

10:34.711 --> 10:36.511
You're welcome.

10:37.297 --> 10:39.714
Column of skitters flows into
the valley here -- 10 o'clock.

10:39.716 --> 10:41.183
We need to send scouts

10:41.218 --> 10:43.218
to follow that column
back to its source --

10:43.270 --> 10:45.971
hopefully, where they're
manufacturing these damn things.

10:46.023 --> 10:47.055
Send Hal.

10:47.107 --> 10:49.057
With, um...
Pope and Sara.

10:49.059 --> 10:50.642
I think
Hal went with Maggie.

10:50.694 --> 10:53.945
He should have brought her back.
I said "all hands on deck."

10:53.981 --> 10:55.981
How about
just Pope and Sara?

10:56.033 --> 10:58.650
We don't need another
Mason family babysitter.

10:58.702 --> 11:00.235
Fine.
Take Sara and move out.

11:00.287 --> 11:01.486
We need
to plug that spigot

11:01.538 --> 11:03.071
before something else
comes out of it.

11:03.073 --> 11:04.239
You want me
to go with him?

11:04.291 --> 11:06.575
Yeah. No.
Uh, I want to talk to you.

11:06.577 --> 11:08.326
I don't suppose
you've had any of those

11:08.378 --> 11:10.212
Woodrow Wilson hunches lately,
have you?

11:10.247 --> 11:12.130
That's what I want
to talk to you about.

11:17.087 --> 11:19.671
So, why do you care this much
about two people you just met?

11:19.723 --> 11:21.473
It's hard to explain.

11:21.508 --> 11:23.508
Well, my brother understands,
right?

11:23.560 --> 11:25.143
Hal, please.

11:25.179 --> 11:26.645
It's --
it's the spikes.

11:26.680 --> 11:29.014
It's like trying
to explain color

11:29.066 --> 11:31.016
to someone who's been blind
their whole life.

11:31.068 --> 11:32.601
Hey.
Help me understand.

11:35.772 --> 11:37.606
When you connect
to someone --

11:37.608 --> 11:40.275
like, right into their mind,
into their soul --

11:40.327 --> 11:42.994
it's emotional,
you know?

11:43.030 --> 11:44.613
You feel
what they feel.

11:44.615 --> 11:46.281
What'd you feel?

11:47.751 --> 11:49.784
That's something
you might understand

11:49.786 --> 11:53.004
more than me,
actually.

11:53.040 --> 11:55.090
Brian was
in so much pain,

11:55.125 --> 11:57.626
and all he cared about
was not hurting his big sister.

11:57.628 --> 12:00.679
Hey, hey, hey.
Hey, hey, hey.

12:00.714 --> 12:03.465
So what do you mean I would understand
better than you would?

12:03.517 --> 12:05.800
Because you grew up
with a family. Okay?

12:05.802 --> 12:07.435
I didn't have that.

12:07.471 --> 12:10.639
So I've never experienced
that kind of connection,

12:10.641 --> 12:12.641
that kind of love.

12:14.228 --> 12:17.145
Until now,
in a really weird way.

12:21.735 --> 12:23.818
[ Spikes crackle ]

12:23.820 --> 12:25.320
They're close.

12:28.325 --> 12:33.128
Yeah, except the eyes were just
a little bit closer together.

12:35.215 --> 12:37.666
I understand
you wanted to see me, Tom Mason.

12:37.718 --> 12:39.251
Yes, I did.

12:39.303 --> 12:42.087
Um, and the leg
was a bit more tapered.

12:43.307 --> 12:45.307
I was hoping
that you could help me.

12:45.342 --> 12:46.841
Um...

12:46.843 --> 12:49.344
I've been having these,
uh...

12:49.396 --> 12:51.179
Visions or memories.

12:51.231 --> 12:52.681
I don't know
exactly what they are,

12:52.733 --> 12:55.183
but there's something in them
that doesn't really belong.

12:55.235 --> 12:57.102
It's kind of a creature,
and I was hoping

12:57.154 --> 12:58.603
that you could help me
identify it.

12:58.655 --> 13:02.157
Dad thinks someone's
communicating with him.

13:02.192 --> 13:03.575
Or <i> something.</i>

13:03.610 --> 13:05.327
I think
it had eight limbs.

13:05.362 --> 13:07.245
I know --
it sounds crazy,

13:07.281 --> 13:10.198
but the information that I've
been getting has had some value.

13:10.250 --> 13:13.335
Roughly 352 known species
have eight appendages

13:13.370 --> 13:15.503
in some sort
of configuration.

13:15.539 --> 13:17.839
Okay. Well,
would you mind taking a look?

13:21.261 --> 13:22.544
You recognize that?

13:22.596 --> 13:25.096
Yes.

13:25.132 --> 13:29.384
What your son has drawn is
a species known as the Dorniya.

13:29.386 --> 13:31.386
So I really did
see something?

13:31.388 --> 13:33.855
I'm afraid
that would be impossible.

13:33.890 --> 13:35.724
The Dorniya are, in fact,
the very species

13:35.726 --> 13:37.525
that the Espheni enslaved

13:37.561 --> 13:40.395
and mutated into skitters
many generations ago.

13:40.397 --> 13:42.530
They have been extinct
from their original form

13:42.566 --> 13:44.649
for hundreds of years.

13:44.701 --> 13:46.234
They're not extinct,

13:46.286 --> 13:48.620
because that is
pretty much what I saw.

13:51.742 --> 13:55.910
Caitlin: Brian, let go of me!
Please let go of me!

13:55.912 --> 13:58.246
Brian!

13:58.248 --> 14:00.215
Maggie: There.

14:00.250 --> 14:02.467
Brian, I'm so scared!

14:02.502 --> 14:04.469
Let me go! Please!

14:04.504 --> 14:06.671
Please! Brian! Brian!

14:06.723 --> 14:08.673
[ Grunts loudly ]

14:08.725 --> 14:10.842
Hey, hey, hey.
Maggie, Maggie. No. No!

14:10.894 --> 14:12.594
Look at me.
Look at me!

14:12.646 --> 14:14.312
No!
Focus. Look at me.

14:14.348 --> 14:15.430
No!
You got this.

14:15.432 --> 14:17.265
[ Grunts ]

14:17.267 --> 14:21.403
[ Caitlin shouting
indistinctly ]

14:21.438 --> 14:23.855
Please let me go!

14:23.907 --> 14:26.491
[ Panting ]

14:26.526 --> 14:28.777
Maggie? Maggie?

14:28.829 --> 14:31.496
[ Caitlin crying ]

14:31.531 --> 14:34.249
Oh, my God!
Brian, please!

14:34.284 --> 14:37.285
Maggie, no!

14:37.287 --> 14:38.536
[ Sobs ]

14:38.588 --> 14:39.621
Brian, no!

14:42.544 --> 14:44.795
He didn't run away.
It wasn't his fault.

14:44.831 --> 14:46.631
I was the one
that was holding him back.

14:46.666 --> 14:48.833
[ Deep voice ] You came back to me,
where you belong.

14:48.885 --> 14:51.919
You should have come alone.
You put my plan in jeopardy.

14:51.921 --> 14:53.838
Soon,
you will rejoin your pack.

14:53.890 --> 14:55.506
Now kill her!

14:55.558 --> 14:56.924
[ Snarls ]

14:56.976 --> 14:59.010
B-Brian!

14:59.062 --> 15:00.062
[ Roars ]

15:02.015 --> 15:04.398
[ Grunting ]
[ Screaming ]

15:06.736 --> 15:08.402
[ Shudders ]

15:12.108 --> 15:15.610
Maggie! No! He might know where
the skitters are being made!

15:17.447 --> 15:18.829
Caitlin:
Brian, don't shoot them!

15:19.699 --> 15:21.032
No!

15:21.084 --> 15:22.833
[ Screeches ]

15:24.370 --> 15:26.587
[ Voice breaking ]
Brian...You hurt me!

15:27.790 --> 15:29.507
Brian, no. No.

15:31.094 --> 15:33.427
Brian, put the gun down!
Please!

15:33.463 --> 15:34.879
[ Roars ]

15:34.931 --> 15:36.797
don't do it!

15:36.799 --> 15:38.549
[ Sobbing ] No!

15:38.601 --> 15:39.601
Brian!

15:39.602 --> 15:40.968
Why?!

15:46.142 --> 15:48.809
Shhh.

15:48.861 --> 15:50.978
[ Weakly ]
Why did he do that?

15:52.448 --> 15:55.816
He didn't want
to hurt you.

15:55.818 --> 15:58.035
And then he just
couldn't stand that he did.

15:58.071 --> 16:01.706
It wa--
wasn't his fault.

16:01.741 --> 16:03.074
I know.

16:03.126 --> 16:05.159
He loved you so much.

16:05.161 --> 16:06.577
I wish I had a brother

16:06.629 --> 16:09.080
who loved me
as much as Brian loved you.

16:10.883 --> 16:13.668
He loved you so much.

16:20.560 --> 16:22.560
[ Sobbing ]

16:26.683 --> 16:28.849
We're burying them
together.

16:34.924 --> 16:36.857
[ Skitters screeching ]

16:48.871 --> 16:51.038
Lions and tigers and skitters.
Oh, my.

16:51.040 --> 16:53.708
We'll be lucky if those are
the only things we run into --

16:53.760 --> 16:55.209
especially
if we keep tracking

16:55.211 --> 16:57.928
this line of skitters upstream
to their source.

16:57.964 --> 16:59.130
[ Chuckles ]

16:59.182 --> 17:01.716
You know,
somehow, I get the feeling

17:01.718 --> 17:04.050
you're used to
going against the flow.

17:04.053 --> 17:06.554
What gave you that idea?

17:06.556 --> 17:08.556
It's funny.

17:08.608 --> 17:11.692
Even with hundreds
of literal monsters

17:11.728 --> 17:15.529
feet away from us,
I'm okay.

17:15.565 --> 17:17.565
I used to be terrified
of woods like this

17:17.617 --> 17:18.898
before the apocalypse.

17:18.901 --> 17:20.233
Yeah, my kids,
they used to be

17:20.236 --> 17:22.569
pretty freaked out
by the woods, as well.

17:22.571 --> 17:23.738
Whoa. Hold the farm.

17:25.958 --> 17:28.125
You have kids?

17:28.161 --> 17:31.495
And y-you didn't think
to mention this before now?

17:31.547 --> 17:35.499
"Had" being
the operative word.

17:36.586 --> 17:39.053
I-I'm so sorry
about what --

17:43.593 --> 17:45.976
Yeah, I-I tried
to adopt a kid once,

17:46.012 --> 17:48.229
but, uh...
They wouldn't let me,

17:48.264 --> 17:51.766
given my record of rehab
and all.

17:51.818 --> 17:52.850
That sucks.

17:52.902 --> 17:54.652
Yeah, well...

17:54.687 --> 17:57.571
And I'd been clean
for about a year, too, but...

17:57.607 --> 17:58.856
Hey.

17:58.908 --> 18:01.025
If you ever want
to talk about them...

18:04.113 --> 18:06.113
You know,
it's never too late.

18:06.165 --> 18:08.666
Have a kid --

18:08.701 --> 18:10.584
the old-fashioned way.

18:10.620 --> 18:12.753
You know, when...

18:12.789 --> 18:14.789
When all this...

18:14.791 --> 18:17.508
This thing ends.

18:17.543 --> 18:21.178
Think you'd make
some really beautiful babies.

18:36.779 --> 18:38.145
Hey.

18:44.871 --> 18:46.954
[ Exhales deeply ]

18:49.625 --> 18:50.741
What's that?

18:50.793 --> 18:52.076
I'm, uh, making a list

18:52.128 --> 18:53.961
of everything I want to keep
about the world,

18:53.996 --> 18:55.629
you know,
when the war's over.

18:55.665 --> 18:57.715
And, uh, everything I think
we should get rid of.

18:57.750 --> 18:59.250
Give me examples.

18:59.302 --> 19:01.001
Okay.

19:01.053 --> 19:05.005
Well, we're gonna lose
dictators, keep democracy.

19:05.007 --> 19:07.057
Lose weapons
people use on each other

19:07.093 --> 19:10.144
and keep weapons
to use on aliens.

19:10.179 --> 19:13.264
Uh, lose anything jerky
or anything pickled.

19:13.316 --> 19:16.684
Keep anything
chocolate-covered.

19:16.736 --> 19:18.569
<i>Anything</i>
chocolate-covered?

19:18.604 --> 19:19.737
Really?

19:19.772 --> 19:21.322
Yeah, like, you know,

19:21.357 --> 19:24.158
pretzels or peanuts
or cherries.

19:24.193 --> 19:26.610
What about French fries
or Brussels spouts?

19:26.662 --> 19:28.028
Why not?

19:28.080 --> 19:32.166
Chocolate covered maggots
or crickets or caterpillars.

19:32.201 --> 19:33.868
[ Chuckling ] That's gross.
[ Snorts ]

19:33.870 --> 19:36.871
What about you?
Anything you want to add?

19:39.842 --> 19:41.008
Yeah.

19:42.261 --> 19:43.878
Can we get rid of death?

19:48.384 --> 19:50.384
Um...

19:50.386 --> 19:51.685
Sure.

19:52.889 --> 19:54.221
Anything to keep?

19:59.362 --> 20:01.645
Yeah.

20:01.697 --> 20:02.813
Family.

20:02.865 --> 20:05.232
I miss my mom.

20:12.291 --> 20:15.876
Hal: Open the gate!
Open it up! Prisoner!

20:15.912 --> 20:17.328
[ Shouting in distance ]

20:17.380 --> 20:19.079
Can we get a little help
over here?!

20:19.131 --> 20:21.749
Man:
It's an overlord!

20:21.751 --> 20:25.052
Somebody grab something
to tie him up tighter!

20:25.087 --> 20:26.087
You guys okay?

20:26.088 --> 20:27.421
Put a rifle on him!

20:27.423 --> 20:29.256
Check these restraints!

20:29.258 --> 20:31.225
Finally -- a break!

20:31.260 --> 20:33.260
Anne: This way!

20:33.312 --> 20:35.262
Come on.

20:40.344 --> 20:42.545
We know
you're making skitters somehow.

20:42.581 --> 20:44.314
I want to know where.

20:44.349 --> 20:45.598
Answer me.

20:45.651 --> 20:47.484
Why? You intend
to torture me anyway.

20:47.519 --> 20:49.102
No, I intend to kill you.

20:49.154 --> 20:50.820
The only question is
how long you suffer first.

20:50.856 --> 20:54.441
I assure you, I can withstand
any pain you may inflict

20:54.493 --> 20:56.609
longer than your son.

20:56.662 --> 20:58.528
Oh,
you might be surprised.

20:58.580 --> 20:59.663
Not likely.

20:59.698 --> 21:02.582
We're done here.

21:02.617 --> 21:04.200
[ Grunts ]

21:04.252 --> 21:05.735
[ Sniffs ]

21:11.276 --> 21:12.475
Did you see anything?

21:12.511 --> 21:13.543
No.

21:13.595 --> 21:15.128
You have to hurt him,
dad.

21:15.180 --> 21:16.846
If I hurt him,
you're gonna feel it.

21:16.882 --> 21:18.465
I can take it.

21:18.517 --> 21:20.266
You have to be merciless.

21:20.302 --> 21:22.469
Come on.
We have to do this.

21:22.521 --> 21:25.555
Oh, believe me, I want to,
but it doesn't serve any purpose

21:25.557 --> 21:27.223
unless
you can outlast him.

21:27.275 --> 21:29.776
Are you positive
that you can?

21:30.812 --> 21:32.112
Forget I said that.

21:32.147 --> 21:33.267
I'll think
of something else.

21:33.281 --> 21:34.281
Dad.

21:46.411 --> 21:49.212
We're kind of far from
the skitter river, aren't we?

21:49.247 --> 21:50.247
[ Chuckles ]

21:50.248 --> 21:52.382
Oh, ye of little faith.

21:52.417 --> 21:55.335
I know this road --
curves west just up ahead.

21:55.387 --> 21:57.754
We're just cutting a corner
here, save a little time.

21:57.756 --> 21:59.556
Whoa! Whoa!

22:01.259 --> 22:04.260
Oh, whoa. No, no.
don't -- don't sweat it.

22:04.262 --> 22:06.312
It's just, uh,
one of those artichoke bombs.

22:06.348 --> 22:07.847
It's all been burnt
to a crisp.

22:07.899 --> 22:09.265
Don't worry about it.

22:09.317 --> 22:10.317
Okay.

22:11.603 --> 22:12.819
Ugh!

22:12.854 --> 22:14.938
It's not <i> all</i>
burnt to a crisp.

22:14.940 --> 22:16.406
I can tell you that.

22:16.441 --> 22:19.242
Stop! No! You're gonna
get stuck! Get back!

22:19.277 --> 22:21.194
It's -- it's under the leaves!
You'll get stuck, too!

22:21.246 --> 22:22.412
This isn't good, honey.

22:22.447 --> 22:24.280
Sara, this is
that Espheni fog crap.

22:24.332 --> 22:25.782
This stuff is like cement!

22:25.784 --> 22:29.619
This stuff's should have been
burnt to a crisp!

22:29.671 --> 22:32.455
Had to have survived
by chilling out in the shade.

22:32.507 --> 22:34.758
That's impossible!

22:34.793 --> 22:36.176
Hold on, hon.

22:36.211 --> 22:37.851
Careful. If you slip,
we'll both be stuck.

22:38.964 --> 22:40.346
[ Grunts ]

22:40.382 --> 22:42.265
Watch it!
Baby, please!

22:42.300 --> 22:43.850
Okay, okay. Okay.

22:45.637 --> 22:47.303
Okay.

22:47.305 --> 22:48.888
We've got to get you out of here.
Okay.

22:48.940 --> 22:51.391
All right, just lift your arms,
and I'm gonna come under here.

22:51.443 --> 22:52.483
You ready?
Okay. All right.

22:52.527 --> 22:54.477
One, two, three --
come on.

22:54.529 --> 22:56.813
[ Grunting ]

22:56.865 --> 22:58.198
Aaaaaaaaaah!

22:58.233 --> 22:59.399
Come on!

22:59.451 --> 23:00.817
Oh, it's like superglue!

23:00.819 --> 23:02.202
It's not working.

23:02.237 --> 23:04.370
Okay. Okay.

23:04.406 --> 23:06.406
What the hell
am I gonna do?

23:06.458 --> 23:08.408
Oh, dear God.

23:08.460 --> 23:09.659
Whoa. Oh, no, no --
fire.

23:09.711 --> 23:12.245
Fire melts this stuff.
Oh.

23:12.297 --> 23:16.416
Well, that'd be great if we had,
like, some...Fire anywhere.

23:17.502 --> 23:18.835
[ Panting ]

23:18.887 --> 23:20.587
Okay.
You have to go back.

23:20.639 --> 23:21.888
You can go back
and get the flamethrower.

23:21.923 --> 23:23.339
No, no. No.
Yeah!

23:23.341 --> 23:24.507
Go get it,
and then you come back,

23:24.509 --> 23:25.842
and you can burn it all up,
okay?

23:25.844 --> 23:27.760
No, no. No. No. No.

23:27.813 --> 23:29.429
I am not --
I am not leaving you.

23:29.481 --> 23:31.397
But w-what else
can we do?

23:31.433 --> 23:33.399
I'm -- I'm -- I'm still armed,
right? Okay?

23:33.435 --> 23:35.435
A-a-and if a skitter
comes through,

23:35.487 --> 23:37.487
they'll get stuck
before they can reach me.

23:37.522 --> 23:40.740
I'm fine. You just go on
and do that, okay?

23:43.862 --> 23:45.945
You listen to me.

23:47.749 --> 23:49.949
You're not
gonna die out here.

23:50.001 --> 23:52.001
I promise you that,
all right?

23:52.037 --> 23:53.419
Right.

23:56.541 --> 23:59.425
I wanted to...

23:59.461 --> 24:01.594
I've been wanting to tell you
something since...

24:03.882 --> 24:05.548
I wanted
to tell you that --

24:05.600 --> 24:06.716
I know.

24:06.718 --> 24:09.018
I feel the same.

24:10.355 --> 24:11.521
You do?

24:11.556 --> 24:13.640
[ Voice breaking ]
I do, yeah.

24:31.877 --> 24:33.960
I swear
I'll be back for you.

24:35.664 --> 24:37.797
[ Grunts ]

24:41.670 --> 24:43.920
[ Breathing heavily ]

24:45.056 --> 24:46.422
Ben: Maggie!

24:46.474 --> 24:47.974
Just the person
I was looking for.

24:48.009 --> 24:50.593
Not too loud, okay?
I have a splitting headache.

24:50.645 --> 24:53.763
Um...Look...

24:53.765 --> 24:55.682
Before I gave you
some of my spikes,

24:55.734 --> 24:57.483
I was really close
to being able

24:57.519 --> 24:59.402
to get inside
the overlords' minds.

24:59.437 --> 25:02.322
I even saw some things
they didn't want me to see.

25:02.357 --> 25:04.657
I-I'm more in control now.
I could probably get through.

25:04.693 --> 25:05.775
I...

25:05.777 --> 25:07.026
I think
I could figure out

25:07.078 --> 25:08.945
where all those skitters
are coming from

25:08.947 --> 25:10.530
if I had all my spikes.

25:10.582 --> 25:11.664
What --
you want them back?

25:11.700 --> 25:13.533
No, I...

25:13.585 --> 25:16.619
If we do it together,
if we use all the spikes,

25:16.671 --> 25:19.839
we might be able
to walk right into his brain.

25:22.093 --> 25:23.543
Will it work?

25:23.595 --> 25:24.677
Honestly,
I don't know.

25:24.713 --> 25:26.095
You might
have to hurt him,

25:26.131 --> 25:28.381
distract his mind
long enough for us to get in.

25:28.433 --> 25:31.134
If I hurt him, you'll feel it.
You understand that, right?

25:31.136 --> 25:34.103
I'd do anything
to get at that son of a bitch.

25:38.526 --> 25:40.693
Let's talk.

25:44.866 --> 25:45.866
By all means.

25:47.118 --> 25:49.152
Where are the new skitters
coming from?

25:49.154 --> 25:51.654
I do not know.

25:51.656 --> 25:52.905
Suit yourself.

26:01.916 --> 26:04.500
I did not ask to be
attached to the female.

26:04.552 --> 26:06.002
Mm. Too bad.

26:06.004 --> 26:08.137
This conversation is over.

26:08.173 --> 26:10.723
[ Grunting ]

26:10.759 --> 26:12.809
Get out of me!
Get out of me.

26:12.844 --> 26:14.677
Get out of me.
Get out of me!

26:16.181 --> 26:18.014
Can't shake them off,
can you?

26:18.066 --> 26:20.066
Show me
what I want to know!

26:20.101 --> 26:21.768
No!
No!

26:21.820 --> 26:22.852
No?

26:22.904 --> 26:24.988
[ Both groaning ]

26:28.493 --> 26:30.193
Okay.

26:30.945 --> 26:33.029
[ Both scream ]

26:33.081 --> 26:34.864
Get out of me!
Get out of me!

26:36.084 --> 26:38.668
Show them what I want to know,
and maybe they will!

26:38.703 --> 26:40.753
[ Both grunting ]

26:40.789 --> 26:42.038
No?

26:42.457 --> 26:45.842
[ Both groaning ]

26:52.133 --> 26:54.550
Dad! What the hell
are you doing?!

26:56.771 --> 26:58.104
Ben, Maggie! Let go!

27:08.233 --> 27:09.233
Maggie!

27:11.236 --> 27:14.070
Ben? Maggie!

27:14.072 --> 27:15.738
You okay?
Can you hear me?

27:15.740 --> 27:18.658
[ Gasping ]

27:18.710 --> 27:20.543
Did you see that?

27:20.578 --> 27:22.662
We got in.
You got in?

27:22.714 --> 27:24.997
Yeah. He's the one making the skitters.
Where?

27:25.050 --> 27:26.749
North of here.
I can find it on a map.

27:26.751 --> 27:27.800
You're positive?
Yeah.

27:29.721 --> 27:31.637
There was something else,
too.

27:31.673 --> 27:34.757
It's...Huge.
It's different.

27:34.809 --> 27:36.676
Different?
Different how?

27:36.728 --> 27:38.010
I don't know, but it was
definitely in charge.

27:38.063 --> 27:39.479
Dad,
we're running out of time.

27:39.514 --> 27:40.847
As soon as they hit
their target number,

27:40.899 --> 27:42.014
they're gonna overrun
the 2nd Mass.

27:42.067 --> 27:43.683
How many? When?
I don't know,

27:43.735 --> 27:45.651
but it felt really close --
<i>really</i> close.

27:45.687 --> 27:47.603
We have to go <i> now --</i>
before they attack.

27:47.605 --> 27:48.938
We need that overlord
alive, Dan.

27:48.990 --> 27:50.690
He may have some answers

27:50.742 --> 27:52.575
about the radio jamming
the Volm have been getting,

27:52.610 --> 27:53.826
especially
in Fayetteville and D.C.

27:53.862 --> 27:55.528
I got a guard on him.

27:55.580 --> 27:57.697
Anne, you were right --
they're engineering them.

27:57.749 --> 27:59.749
Skitters and hornets
at a turtle hatchery.

27:59.784 --> 28:01.751
It's on the map --
nine klicks to the northeast.

28:01.786 --> 28:03.586
Ben and Maggie --
we need them.

28:03.621 --> 28:05.505
No, they need
a little recovery time.

28:05.540 --> 28:07.757
The rest of you are gonna
come with us! In the truck!

28:07.792 --> 28:10.510
Except Dingaan. You and Matt take that
drone up to the valley.

28:10.545 --> 28:13.045
Wait there till you hear
one hell of an explosion.

28:13.098 --> 28:14.964
[ Engine turns over ]

28:18.603 --> 28:20.803
Whoa, whoa, whoa, whoa!
Whoa!

28:22.190 --> 28:23.523
Slide over. I'll drive.
What are you talking about?

28:23.558 --> 28:25.141
Sara --
she's in big trouble.

28:25.143 --> 28:27.276
She got stuck in some of that
leftover Espheni fog crap.

28:27.312 --> 28:28.811
How far out is she?

28:28.863 --> 28:31.147
10, 11 klicks.
I ran the whole way here. South.

28:31.149 --> 28:33.649
Look, I need the truck, get back to her
before anything else beats us to it.

28:33.651 --> 28:34.811
Can we pick her up
on the way?

28:34.819 --> 28:36.536
The opposite direction.
Of what?

28:36.571 --> 28:38.121
We know where
they're making skitters.

28:38.156 --> 28:39.822
There's a major offensive
coming our way within the hour.

28:39.824 --> 28:41.040
We have to blow up
their operation.

28:41.075 --> 28:42.708
No, no! No!
We get Sara first.

28:42.744 --> 28:44.544
Mason, this time,
<i>my</i> family comes first.

28:44.579 --> 28:46.712
We blow the place,
we circle back, we'll get Sara.

28:46.748 --> 28:47.964
You got my word.

28:47.999 --> 28:49.799
Your word?!
Mason, how about this?

28:49.834 --> 28:51.918
How about I drag your ass
out of this truck,

28:51.970 --> 28:54.921
I take the truck,
I save Sara's life,

28:54.973 --> 28:56.020
then I turn around and blow up
whatever the hell it is --

28:56.044 --> 28:57.641
I can't think of everybody,
Pope! I'm sorry!

28:57.642 --> 28:59.759
You son of a bitch!

28:59.811 --> 29:02.011
No!! No!!

29:02.013 --> 29:03.896
Mason!!

29:08.186 --> 29:09.602
Open the gate!

29:09.654 --> 29:11.354
Man:
Open up the gate!

29:13.691 --> 29:15.775
[ Skitters screeching ]

29:25.286 --> 29:27.170
Weaver:
This ain't gonna be easy.

29:27.205 --> 29:29.005
I'd say our best bet
is to go around the back.

29:29.007 --> 29:30.339
Yeah, especially
since those bastards

29:30.375 --> 29:32.208
are all streaming
out the <i> front.</i>

29:32.260 --> 29:33.926
All right,
Hal, Anthony, you're with me.

29:33.962 --> 29:35.928
The rest of you,
when they blow the building,

29:35.964 --> 29:38.130
we're gonna put a dent into everything
that comes running out.

29:38.183 --> 29:40.049
Not everything.

29:40.051 --> 29:41.217
Come on. Go.

29:45.974 --> 29:48.107
[ Chittering continues ]

29:58.236 --> 30:00.069
Oh, my God.

30:07.829 --> 30:10.796
They're so cute
when they're newborns.

30:10.832 --> 30:13.082
Yeah.

30:13.134 --> 30:15.001
Hey. Hey.

30:17.805 --> 30:18.805
Yeah?

30:39.814 --> 30:41.480
Anne: Come on, Tom.

30:41.482 --> 30:43.448
They've been in there
a long time.

30:43.484 --> 30:45.067
They'll make it.

30:45.119 --> 30:47.236
God, they should be out
already.

30:49.323 --> 30:51.156
Ho!
Down!

30:51.158 --> 30:53.125
There should be
two more bombs.

30:53.160 --> 30:55.294
Screw the bombs!
They should be out already!

30:56.881 --> 30:59.464
There they are!

30:59.500 --> 31:01.300
Come on! Come on!

31:03.170 --> 31:05.170
Open fire!

31:07.007 --> 31:09.007
[ Skitters screeching ]

31:12.012 --> 31:14.179
Cease fire!

31:14.231 --> 31:15.848
Cease fire!

31:21.989 --> 31:23.272
All clear!

31:23.324 --> 31:24.406
All clear!

31:24.441 --> 31:26.108
[ Exhales deeply ]

31:26.160 --> 31:27.192
Whew.

31:35.536 --> 31:36.835
Is Anthony all right?

31:36.871 --> 31:37.871
Uh...

31:37.872 --> 31:38.921
What happened
in there?

31:38.956 --> 31:40.205
He froze up.

31:43.928 --> 31:45.460
Think maybe
you better talk to him.

31:45.512 --> 31:47.129
Right.

31:47.181 --> 31:48.847
Get everybody to the truck now.
We need to go find Sara.

31:48.883 --> 31:50.465
Do you think
there's still time to save her?

31:50.517 --> 31:52.050
Yeah.

31:52.102 --> 31:54.186
Sara, I got it!
We're --

31:54.221 --> 31:56.188
[ creatures screeching ]

31:56.223 --> 31:58.223
No!

32:04.315 --> 32:08.984
Nooooooooooooooooooooo!!

32:12.239 --> 32:14.289
Sara?!

32:14.325 --> 32:15.991
Sara!

32:17.912 --> 32:18.961
Hey.

32:18.996 --> 32:20.412
Hey.

32:21.582 --> 32:23.081
[ Weakly ] You came.

32:23.083 --> 32:25.083
Yeah.
Yeah, I came --

32:28.088 --> 32:30.339
I can't feel my legs.

32:30.391 --> 32:32.808
No, no, no, no.
Don't...

32:32.843 --> 32:34.977
Don't look -- don't look down,
baby. don't look down.

32:35.012 --> 32:37.095
Okay? You're fine.
You're gonna be fine.

32:37.097 --> 32:39.932
Okay? You just...

32:39.984 --> 32:41.934
You --

32:41.986 --> 32:44.102
[ voice breaking ] You keep --
you keep looking at <i> me.</i>

32:44.104 --> 32:47.322
[ Chuckling ] Now,
why would I want to do that?

32:47.358 --> 32:50.108
[ Chuckles ]

32:55.115 --> 32:58.617
[ Voice breaking ] I...Guess I won't be
having that pretty baby.

33:01.088 --> 33:02.504
John.

33:02.539 --> 33:07.426
Remember how I said
that the apocalypse

33:07.461 --> 33:09.962
was the best thing
that ever happened to me?

33:12.466 --> 33:15.183
I lied.

33:18.105 --> 33:21.473
<i>You're</i> the best thing.

33:37.541 --> 33:39.875
No.

33:39.910 --> 33:43.045
[ Sniffles ]

33:43.080 --> 33:44.629
No.

33:46.000 --> 33:47.332
[ Sniffles ]

33:47.334 --> 33:49.134
[ Whimpering ] No.

33:49.169 --> 33:51.003
No!

33:51.005 --> 33:52.054
No.

33:56.226 --> 33:57.559
[ Sobbing ]

33:57.594 --> 34:00.095
[ Vehicle approaches ]

34:03.017 --> 34:05.017
Tom:
There. There they are.

34:14.161 --> 34:15.360
Pope?

34:21.001 --> 34:22.199
[ Gasps ]

34:22.202 --> 34:24.002
Oh, my God.

34:24.038 --> 34:27.255
[ Voice breaking ]
You're too late.

34:27.291 --> 34:29.958
You're too late, Mason.

34:55.350 --> 34:57.350
[ Growls ]

35:04.076 --> 35:06.192
Colonel Weaver sent me
to spell you.

35:06.228 --> 35:08.328
Why don't you
get some shut-eye?

35:08.363 --> 35:10.263
Uhh.

35:10.299 --> 35:12.032
All right.

35:21.209 --> 35:22.209
What is that?!

35:22.210 --> 35:23.677
Drop it!

35:23.712 --> 35:26.546
Whatever it is,
drop it!

35:26.548 --> 35:29.549
I said drop it!

35:34.272 --> 35:36.306
[ Screaming ]

35:43.448 --> 35:46.116
[ Hurried footsteps ]

35:46.151 --> 35:47.484
Anthony!

35:51.990 --> 35:53.573
Oh, my God.

36:07.339 --> 36:08.972
We needed this thing
alive.

36:09.007 --> 36:11.007
He had a weapon.

36:11.059 --> 36:12.759
T-t-t-- he--
look at his --

36:14.179 --> 36:15.345
I don't see a weapon.

36:15.397 --> 36:16.596
I swear --

36:16.648 --> 36:18.314
I swear
he had a weapon.

36:19.685 --> 36:22.435
Look, I saw a weapon.

36:23.605 --> 36:27.157
Anthony, what are you
even doing here?

36:27.192 --> 36:29.275
I thought
Franks was on duty.

36:31.246 --> 36:32.779
I thought
he could use a break.

36:43.375 --> 36:45.091
Those were not my orders.

36:47.179 --> 36:49.429
Anthony?

36:49.464 --> 36:52.716
Did you come here
intending to kill this overlord?

36:52.768 --> 36:54.267
He had it coming.

36:54.302 --> 36:55.385
[ Sighs deeply ]

36:56.471 --> 36:58.722
"He had it coming"?

36:58.774 --> 37:02.442
Anthony, he could have
told us so much!

37:02.477 --> 37:04.811
This is <i> my</i> fault.

37:04.813 --> 37:07.480
This is
classic PTSD behavior.

37:07.532 --> 37:09.315
When I heard
he froze at the hatchery,

37:09.317 --> 37:10.650
I should have
taken his weapon.

37:10.702 --> 37:12.702
Taken my what?!
don't take me out the fight.

37:12.738 --> 37:16.489
Clearly, you are a danger
to yourself and to others.

37:16.491 --> 37:18.041
Colonel!

37:18.076 --> 37:20.076
I've done as much
for the 2nd Mass as anybody.

37:20.128 --> 37:21.411
You need me!

37:21.463 --> 37:23.379
Yes, I do.

37:24.633 --> 37:26.082
Which makes this
even harder.

37:55.280 --> 37:57.664
Maggie: Hey.

37:57.699 --> 38:00.583
Feel like I just ran
100 miles uphill

38:00.619 --> 38:02.752
[ strained ] With someone
kicking me in the stomach.

38:02.788 --> 38:05.505
I'm sorry
you had to go through that.

38:06.541 --> 38:09.592
I've seen a lot
in my life.

38:09.628 --> 38:13.296
Today was...Beyond.

38:13.348 --> 38:15.515
I mean...

38:15.550 --> 38:18.635
Being inside
an overlord's mind?

38:19.805 --> 38:24.524
F-for my first time,
I...

38:24.559 --> 38:26.860
T-that kid
was in so much pain.

38:26.895 --> 38:28.695
I never...

38:30.315 --> 38:32.565
It's...

38:32.567 --> 38:35.652
Yeah,
it's -- it's a nightmare.

38:35.704 --> 38:37.737
I know.

38:39.207 --> 38:40.790
I'm glad you were there
with me today.

38:40.826 --> 38:43.626
I don't know how you've
done this alone for three years.

38:43.662 --> 38:45.211
It's crazy.

38:52.504 --> 38:54.804
Dingaan and Matt crop-dusted
the last of the skitters.

38:54.840 --> 38:57.557
We got a clear road
north.

39:01.930 --> 39:03.263
Tom?

39:06.601 --> 39:08.568
Yeah.
Yeah, yeah, yeah.

39:08.603 --> 39:10.737
Okay. 86 the fire.
Pack up the gear.

39:10.772 --> 39:12.272
I'm ready
to go to Fayetteville.

39:12.324 --> 39:14.607
Nah. This group
needs some downtime.

39:14.609 --> 39:16.826
We can pack up
in the morning.

39:18.947 --> 39:20.363
Yeah, you're right.

39:23.668 --> 39:25.869
Why don't you go
get a drink -- on me?

39:25.921 --> 39:27.921
You can count on that.

39:29.624 --> 39:31.541
You okay?

39:33.678 --> 39:36.296
Do you think we should have
gone to get her first?

39:40.685 --> 39:41.885
No.

39:44.439 --> 39:47.941
I just remember a time
when you <i> would</i> have.

39:51.479 --> 39:53.947
Thanks, Dan.

39:53.982 --> 39:55.315
[ Pats ]

39:55.317 --> 39:56.866
Get some sleep.

39:56.902 --> 39:58.534
Long way to D.C.

39:58.570 --> 40:01.654
Yep. You too.

40:05.410 --> 40:07.827
D.C.?
Without any Volm Intel?

40:07.879 --> 40:09.829
No, we're going
to Fayetteville first.

40:09.881 --> 40:10.914
Okay.

40:10.966 --> 40:12.832
Find out
what they're hiding.

40:14.836 --> 40:17.720
Something's going on
in D.C., though.

40:21.760 --> 40:23.343
Hard call today.

40:23.395 --> 40:24.844
Not the first.

40:26.348 --> 40:28.014
Not the last.

